has been described e.g. in Refs \cite{MuBa02,ChaRieAbr05}.
Notice that in the case of a Gaussian $\omega_\ell(t)$, a simpler 
and faster FFT method can be directly used.
In order to simulate samples of $\delta_{\gamma_\ell(t)}$ in Eq. \eqref{defmu2}, one starts with a signal of constant value sampled at frequency $2 \ell$ and one discretises the logarithms of the scales $\ln(\ell) \leq v = \ln(s) \leq \ln(T)$ in small strips of width $\Delta v$ (typically one chooses $\Delta v$ in order to have around 100 strips between $\ell$ and $T$). 
One then generates in each strip a Poisson point 
process in time of intensity $(1-D) e^{-v} \Delta v$ as given by
Eq. \eqref{intensity}. For each of the obtained events $(t_i,s_i)$, we set to zero all the signal values in the interval $(t_i-s_i/2,t_i+s_i/2)$.
The examples considered in this section are built in that way.
